replies.comment info:
@Aidan Griffin
I think the fast-food bubble moved about 25% down because, like most of the other things on the left side of the graph, that would require people to leave their houses more frequently and unnecessarily, thus risking spreading and/or catching the virus. Even though fast food places are still doing service and people are still going, my guess is many people would rather support their local businesses with takeout orders if they're going to eat out at all. 

I didn't even think about the health impact of our spending during COVID. Because of the decrease in fast food and the rise in grocery purchases, it's true that most people are probably eating healthier. But I don't see why they wouldn't be buying frozen foods in their groceries in addition to fresh foods (except for possibly purchases from the online grocers). I also noticed that the spending on "fitness" went down nearly 75%. There's a chance that has caused people to exercise less, but I know if they're anything like me or my neighbors, they've been spending a lot of time exercising on their own without a gym or new equipment, doing things such as running, walking, biking, and bodyweight-exercises. So altogether, I think you're right that people will become at least slightly more healthy.

@Jonathan 
What would you consider to be "essential?"
To me, it makes sense that people who have the money to do so, can and will take the time to improve their surroundings. Also, general merchandise is a pretty broad category.

@Ryan Boaz, This was a great explanation of what is happening in the graph, as well as useful insights. Just like you, I was surprised to see the supermarkets seemed to be neutral. The bubble size indicates that the industry sales of supermarkets are high. Which could mean people are still going to the store like normal, but spending more money on potentially expensive products because of brand limitations. 

You had an interesting point that though some people are doing well, others aren't, and shouldn't that be a concern. The government has tried to help by turning schools into places to get food, as well as putting in place economic impact payments made for families who require money. 

Overall though, you're right that Covod-19 is leaving a wake of economic disaster behind it. Many local places are struggling, and I believe that after this, lots of previously struggling stores might be filing for bankruptcy.
